        "is_accepted": false,
        "last_activity_date": 1386380490,
        "creation_date": 1386379191,
        "body": "<p>The best practise is: Don't use this.<\/p>\n\n<p>Make a Class Employee with members<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Employee {\n    String id; \n    List&lt;Long&gt; projectIds;\n    List&lt;String&gt; performanceGoals;\n\n    ...\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>And you method changes to:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public Employee getEmployeeInfo(String query) {\n    ...\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p><strong>update for clarification why returning Map is bad in general<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>If your method returns:<\/p>\n\n<p><code>Map&lt;String,?&gt;<\/code> or <code>Map&lt;String,? extends Object&gt;<\/code> you say (in slang):<\/p>\n\n<p><em>Hey look here, I am returning something. Store it in a variable called \"something\", because I don't say anything about the value.<\/em><\/p>\n\n<p>If you write this method, you have to ensure, that you know every single line of code, where you work with your Map. <\/p>\n\n<p>Lets say I would like to change <code>employeeId<\/code> from <code>String<\/code> to <code>Integer<\/code>. This will lead to really bad <code>RuntimeExceptions<\/code> and <code>ClassCastExceptions<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
        "answer_id": 20436374,
        "question_id": 20436220,
        "last_edit_date": 1386380490
    }],
